; how the segmentation of beauty culture (i.e., the sale of black beauty products on store shelves labelled “ethnic hair care”) occurred in Canada; and how black beauty culture, which was generally seen as a small niche market before the 1970s, entered Canada’s mainstream by way of department stores, drugstores, and big-box retailers. Beauty in a Box uses an interdisciplinary framework, engaging with African American history, critical race and cultural theory, consumer culture theory, media studies, diasporic art history, black feminism, visual culture, film studies, and political economy to explore the history of black beauty culture in both Canada and the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American womenxRace identity. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aBeauty culturexSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBeauty, PersonalxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBeauty, PersonalzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBeauty, PersonalzUnited States. 0aHairxSocial aspectszUnited States. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 4aSocial Science: Multiculturalism. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aAfrican Canadians.  aAfros.  aBlack beauty.  aChatelaine.  aEbony-magazine.  aNew Negro.  aViola Desmond.  abeauty pageants.  ablack hair.  ablack-magazines.  ablacknewspapers.  achemical relaxers.  afashion.  ahair straightening.  ahair weaves.  amodels.  askin-bleaching.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112359440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123594423Coveru